                            <comment id="12795755" author="jsguru72" created="Fri, 1 Jan 2010 14:46:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The simple fix for this would be to change the exit command to a return command.  This will return the script to the user&apos;s shell with the indicated return code, but will not exit the shell itself. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here is the relevant code.&lt;br/&gt;
if [ -z &quot;$DERBY_HOME&quot; ] ; then&lt;br/&gt;
  echo &quot;Error: DERBY_HOME is not set. Please set the DERBY_HOME environment variable&quot;&lt;br/&gt;
  echo &quot;to the location of your Derby installation.&quot;&lt;br/&gt;
  return 1   #This will return a code of &apos;1&apos; to the users shell without exiting the shell&lt;br/&gt;
fi&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
